n Bergeaud’s homeland. Unique among nineteenth-century accounts, Stella gives a pro-Haitian version of the Haitian Revolution, a bloody but just struggle that emancipated a people, and it charges future generations with remembering the sacrifices and glory of their victory. Bergeaud's novel demonstrates that the Haitians-not the French-are the true inheritors of the French Revolution, and that Haiti is the realization of its republican ideals. At a time in which Haitian Studies is becoming increasingly important within the English-speaking world, this edition calls attention to the rich though under-examined world of nineteenth-century Haiti.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Caribbean & West Indies / General.2bisacsh1 aArdouin, B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurtis, Lesley S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurtis, Lesley S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMucher, Christen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMucher, Christen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479895427.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479895427423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479895427/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles